# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: circuit-breaker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In an electric circuit, instantaneous power is the time rate of flow of energy past a given point of the circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In alternating current circuits, energy storage elements such as inductors and capacitors may result in periodic reversals of the direction of energy flow.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that, averaged over a complete cycle of the AC waveform, results in net transfer of energy in one direction is known as instantaneous active power, and its time average is known as **active power** or **real power**.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The portion of instantaneous power that results in no net transfer of energy but instead oscillates between the source and load in each cycle due to stored energy is known as instantaneous reactive power, and its amplitude is the absolute value of **reactive power**.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The **instantaneous power** is given by the product: $p(t)=v(t)i(t)=2{|V|}{|I|}\cos(\omega t)\cos(\omega t-\varphi ).$ If the load is purely resistive, the two quantities reverse their polarity at the same time.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Hence, the instantaneous power is always positive, such that the direction of energy flow does not reverse and always is toward the resistor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In this case, only active power is transferred.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] If the load is purely *reactive*, then the voltage and current are 90 degrees out of phase.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] For two quarters of each cycle, the product of voltage and current is positive, but for the other two quarters, the product is negative, indicating that on average, exactly as much energy flows into the load as flows back out.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] There is no net energy flow over each half cycle.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In this case, only reactive power flows: There is no net transfer of energy to the load; however, electrical power does flow along the wires and returns by flowing in reverse along the same wires.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The current required for this reactive power flow dissipates energy in the line resistance, even if the ideal load device consumes no energy itself.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Practical loads have resistance as well as inductance, or capacitance, so both active and reactive powers will flow to normal loads.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Apparent power is the product of the RMS values of voltage and current.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Apparent power is taken into account when designing and operating power systems, because although the current associated with reactive power does no work at the load, it still must be supplied by the power source.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Conductors, transformers and generators must be sized to carry the total current, not just the current that does useful work.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Insufficient reactive power can depress voltage levels on an electrical grid and, under certain operating conditions, collapse the network (a blackout).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Another consequence is that adding the apparent power for two loads will not accurately give the total power unless they have the same phase difference between current and voltage (the same power factor).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Conventionally, capacitors are treated as if they generate reactive power, and inductors are treated as if they consume it.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] If a capacitor and an inductor are placed in parallel, then the currents flowing through the capacitor and the inductor tend to cancel rather than add.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This is the fundamental mechanism for controlling the power factor in electric power transmission; capacitors (or inductors) are inserted in a circuit to partially compensate for reactive power 'consumed' ('generated') by the load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Purely capacitive circuits supply reactive power with the current waveform leading the voltage waveform by 90 degrees, while purely inductive circuits absorb reactive power with the current waveform lagging the voltage waveform by 90 degrees.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The result of this is that capacitive and inductive circuit elements tend to cancel each other out.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] These are all denoted in the adjacent diagram (called a power triangle).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In the diagram, *P* is the active power, *Q* is the reactive power (in this case positive), *S* is the complex power and the length of *S* is the apparent power.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Reactive power does not do any work, so it is represented as the **imaginary axis** of the vector diagram.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Active power does do work, so it is the real axis.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The unit for power is the watt (symbol: W).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Apparent power is often expressed in volt-amperes (VA) since it is the product of RMS voltage and RMS current.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The unit for reactive power is var, which stands for volt-ampere reactive.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Since reactive power transfers no net energy to the load, it is sometimes called "wattless" power.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] It does, however, serve an important function in electrical grids and its lack has been cited as a significant factor in the Northeast blackout of 2003.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Understanding the relationship among these three quantities lies at the heart of understanding power engineering.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The mathematical relationship among them can be represented by vectors or expressed using complex numbers, *S* = *P* + *j Q* (where *j* is the imaginary unit).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] where V and I are the complex valued voltage and current, respectively, written in phasor form with the amplitude as RMS.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Also by convention, the complex conjugate of *I* is used, which is denoted $I^{*}$ (or ${\overline {I}}$ ), rather than *I* itself.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This is done because otherwise using the product V I to define S would result in a quantity that depends on the reference angle chosen for V or I, but defining S as V I* results in a quantity that doesn't depend on the reference angle and allows to relate S to P and Q.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Other forms of complex power (units in volt-amps, VA) are derived from *Z*, the load impedance (units in ohms, Ω).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] where *X* denotes reactance (units in ohms, Ω) of the load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] These are simplified diagrammatically by the power triangle.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The ratio of active power to apparent power in a circuit is called the power factor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] For two systems transmitting the same amount of active power, the system with the lower power factor will have higher circulating currents due to energy that returns to the source from energy storage in the load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] These higher currents produce higher losses and reduce overall transmission efficiency.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] A lower power factor circuit will have a higher apparent power and higher losses for the same amount of active power.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The power factor is 1.0 when the voltage and current are in phase.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] It is zero when the current leads or lags the voltage by 90 degrees.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] When the voltage and current are 180 degrees out of phase, the power factor is negative one, and the load is feeding energy into the source (an example would be a home with solar cells on the roof that feed power into the power grid when the sun is shining).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Power factors are usually stated as "leading" or "lagging" to show the sign of the phase angle of current with respect to voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Voltage is designated as the base to which current angle is compared, meaning that current is thought of as either "leading" or "lagging" voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Where the waveforms are purely sinusoidal, the power factor is the cosine of the phase angle ( $\varphi$ ) between the current and voltage sinusoidal waveforms.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Equipment data sheets and nameplates will often abbreviate power factor as " $\cos \varphi$ " for this reason.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Example: The active power is 700 W and the phase angle between voltage and current is 45.6°.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In a direct current circuit, the power flowing to the load is proportional to the product of the current through the load and the potential drop across the load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The power that happens because of a capacitor or inductor is called reactive power.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] It happens because of the AC nature of elements like inductors and capacitors.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Energy flows in one direction from the source to the load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In AC power, the voltage and current both vary approximately sinusoidally.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] When there is inductance or capacitance in the circuit, the voltage and current waveforms do not line up perfectly.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The power flow has two components – one component flows from source to load and can perform work at the load; the other portion, known as "reactive power", is due to the delay between voltage and current, known as phase angle, and cannot do useful work at the load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] It can be thought of as current that is arriving at the wrong time (too late or too early).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] To distinguish reactive power from active power, it is measured in units of "volt-amperes reactive", or var.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] These units can simplify to watts but are left as var to denote that they represent no actual work output.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Energy stored in capacitive or inductive elements of the network gives rise to reactive power flow.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Reactive power flow strongly influences the voltage levels across the network.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Voltage levels and reactive power flow must be carefully controlled to allow a power system to be operated within acceptable limits.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] A technique known as reactive compensation is used to reduce apparent power flow to a load by reducing reactive power supplied from transmission lines and providing it locally.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] For example, to compensate an inductive load, a shunt capacitor is installed close to the load itself.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This allows all reactive power needed by the load to be supplied by the capacitor and not have to be transferred over the transmission lines.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This practice saves energy because it reduces the amount of energy that is required to be produced by the utility to do the same amount of work.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Additionally, it allows for more efficient transmission line designs using smaller conductors or fewer bundled conductors and optimizing the design of transmission towers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Stored energy in the magnetic or electric field of a load device, such as a motor or capacitor, causes an offset between the current and the voltage waveforms.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] A capacitor is a device that stores energy in the form of an electric field.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] As current is driven through the capacitor, charge build-up causes an opposing voltage to develop across the capacitor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This voltage increases until some maximum dictated by the capacitor structure.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In an AC network, the voltage across a capacitor is constantly changing.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The capacitor opposes this change, causing the current to lead the voltage in phase.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Capacitors are said to "source" reactive power, and thus to cause a leading power factor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Induction machines are some of the most common types of loads in the electric power system today.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] These machines use inductors, or large coils of wire to store energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] When a voltage is initially placed across the coil, the inductor strongly resists this change in a current and magnetic field, which causes a time delay for the current to reach its maximum value.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This causes the current to lag behind the voltage in phase.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Inductors are said to "sink" reactive power, and thus to cause a lagging power factor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Induction generators can source or sink reactive power, and provide a measure of control to system operators over reactive power flow and thus voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Because these devices have opposite effects on the phase angle between voltage and current, they can be used to "cancel out" each other's effects.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This usually takes the form of capacitor banks being used to counteract the lagging power factor caused by induction motors.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Transmission connected generators are generally required to support reactive power flow.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] For example, on the United Kingdom transmission system, generators are required by the Grid Code Requirements to supply their rated power between the limits of 0.85 power factor lagging and 0.90 power factor leading at the designated terminals.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The "system gain" is an important source of reactive power in the above power balance equation, which is generated by the capacitative nature of the transmission network itself.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] By making decisive switching actions in the early morning before the demand increases, the system gain can be maximized early on, helping to secure the system for the whole day.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] To balance the equation some pre-fault reactive generator use will be required.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Other sources of reactive power that will also be used include shunt capacitors, shunt reactors, static VAR compensators and voltage control circuits.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] While active power and reactive power are well defined in any system, the definition of apparent power for unbalanced polyphase systems is considered to be one of the most controversial topics in power engineering.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Originally, apparent power arose merely as a figure of merit.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Major delineations of the concept are attributed to Stanley's *Phenomena of Retardation in the Induction Coil* (1888) and Steinmetz's *Theoretical Elements of Engineering* (1915).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] However, with the development of three-phase power distribution, it became clear that the definition of apparent power and the power factor could not be applied to unbalanced polyphase systems.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In 1920, a "Special Joint Committee of the AIEE and the National Electric Light Association" met to resolve the issue.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] that is, the magnitude of total three-phase complex power.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The 1920 committee found no consensus and the topic continued to dominate discussions.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In 1932, another committee formed and once again failed to resolve the question.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] The transcripts of their discussions are the lengthiest and most controversial ever published by the AIEE.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Further resolution of this debate did not come until the late 1990s.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] $V^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence voltage phasor, and $I^{+}$ denotes the positive sequence current phasor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] A perfect resistor stores no energy; so current and voltage are in phase.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Therefore, there is no reactive power and $P=S$ (using the passive sign convention).
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] For a perfect capacitor or inductor, there is no net power transfer; so all power is reactive.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] where *X* is the reactance of the capacitor or inductor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] where $v(t)$ and $i(t)$ are the time-varying voltage and current waveforms.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This definition is useful because it applies to all waveforms, whether they are sinusoidal or not.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This is particularly useful in power electronics, where non-sinusoidal waveforms are common.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In general, engineers are interested in the active power averaged over a period of time, whether it is a low frequency line cycle or a high frequency power converter switching period.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] This method of calculating the average power gives the active power regardless of harmonic content of the waveform.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Since an RMS value can be calculated for any waveform, apparent power can be calculated from this.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] For active power it would at first appear that it would be necessary to calculate many product terms and average all of them.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] However, looking at one of these product terms in more detail produces a very interesting result.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] However, the time average of a function of the form cos(*ωt* + *k*) is zero provided that *ω* is nonzero.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Therefore, the only product terms that have a nonzero average are those where the frequency of voltage and current match.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] In other words, it is possible to calculate active (average) power by simply treating each frequency separately and adding up the answers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Furthermore, if voltage of the mains supply is assumed to be a single frequency (which it usually is), this shows that harmonic currents are a bad thing.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] They will increase the RMS current (since there will be non-zero terms added) and therefore apparent power, but they will have no effect on the active power transferred.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Hence, harmonic currents will reduce the power factor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Harmonic currents can be reduced by a filter placed at the input of the device.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] Typically this will consist of either just a capacitor (relying on parasitic resistance and inductance in the supply) or a capacitor-inductor network.
[src:circuit-breaker/ac-power] An active power factor correction circuit at the input would generally reduce the harmonic currents further and maintain the power factor closer to unity.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:circuit-breaker/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The **ampere** (/ˈæmpɛər/ ⓘ *AM-pair*, US: /ˈæmpɪər/ ⓘ *AM-peer*; symbol: **A**), often shortened to **amp**, is the unit of electric current in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] One ampere is equal to 1 coulomb (C) moving past a point per second.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] It is named after French mathematician and physicist André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), considered the father of electromagnetism along with Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Prior to the redefinition, the ampere was defined as the current passing through two parallel wires 1 metre apart that produces a magnetic force of 2×10−7 newtons per metre.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The earlier CGS system has two units of current, one structured similarly to the SI's and the other using Coulomb's law as a fundamental relationship, with the CGS unit of charge defined by measuring the force between two charged metal plates.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The CGS unit of current is then defined as one unit of charge per second.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The ampere is named for French physicist and mathematician André-Marie Ampère (1775–1836), who studied electromagnetism and laid the foundation of electrodynamics.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] In recognition of Ampère's contributions to the creation of modern electrical science, an international convention, signed at the 1881 International Exposition of Electricity, established the ampere as a standard unit of electrical measurement for electric current.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The ampere was originally defined as one tenth of the unit of electric current in the centimetre–gram–second system of units.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] That unit, now known as the abampere, was defined as the amount of current that generates a force of two dynes per centimetre of length between two wires one centimetre apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The size of the unit was chosen so that the units derived from it in the MKSA system would be conveniently sized.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The "international ampere" was an early realisation of the ampere, defined as the current that would deposit 0.001118 grams of silver per second from a silver nitrate solution.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Later, more accurate measurements revealed that this current is 0.99985 A.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Since power is defined as the product of current and voltage, the ampere can alternatively be expressed in terms of the other units using the relationship *I* = *P*/*V*, and thus 1 A = 1 W/V.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Current can be measured by a multimeter, a device that can measure electrical voltage, current, and resistance.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Ampère's force law states that there is an attractive or repulsive force between two parallel wires carrying an electric current.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] This force was used in the formal definition of the ampere, giving the vacuum magnetic permeability (magnetic constant, *μ*0) a value of exactly 4π × 10−7 henries per metre (H/m, equivalent to N/A2).
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, was then defined as "the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] In general, charge Q was determined by steady current I flowing for a time t as *Q* = *It*.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Techniques to establish the realisation of an ampere had a relative uncertainty of approximately a few parts in 107, and involved realisations of the watt, the ohm and the volt.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The SI unit of charge, the coulomb, "is the quantity of electricity carried in 1 second by a current of 1 ampere".
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] The relation of the ampere (A = C/s) to the coulomb (C) is the same as that of the watt (W = J/s) to the joule (J).
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] These SI derived units can either be given special names e.g. watt, volt, lux, etc. or defined in terms of others, e.g. metre per second.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] There are also some SI units that are frequently used in the context of electrical engineering and electrical appliances, but are defined independently of the ampere, notably the hertz, joule, watt, candela, lumen, and lux.
[src:circuit-breaker/ampere] Like other SI units, the ampere can be modified by adding a prefix that multiplies it by a power of 10.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] "Ancillary services are all services required by the transmission or distribution system operator to enable them to maintain the integrity and stability of the transmission or distribution system as well as the power quality".
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Ancillary services are specialty services and functions provided by actors within the electric grid that facilitate and support the continuous flow of electricity, so that the demand for electrical energy is met in real time.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] The term ancillary services is used to refer to a variety of operations beyond generation and transmission that are required to maintain grid stability and security.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] These services generally include active power control or frequency control and reactive power control or voltage control, on various timescales.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Traditionally, ancillary services have been provided by large production units such as synchronous generators.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] With the integration of more intermittent generation and the development of smart grid technologies, the provision of ancillary services is extended to smaller distributed generation and consumption units.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Electricity frequency is directly connected to the balance of consumption and generation of active power ( $\Delta P=P_{generation}-P_{consume}$ ) and the total rotating energy ( $W_{tot,kin}$ ) of the synchronous power system.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Where S is the total exchange of active power for the entire grid and H is the normalized inertia constant for the system.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] A system with a small amount of total rotating kinetic energy will be more sensitive to deviations in $\Delta P$ , as the frequency's derivative will be more significantly affected.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] As the total inertia of synchronous grids decreases due to the increasing integration of renewable generation sources, the methodologies and requirements for enabling converter-based generation units to control grid frequency with greater speed and precision are becoming more important.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Frequency control refers to the need to ensure that the grid frequency stays within a specific range of the nominal frequency.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Mismatch between electricity generation and demand causes variations in frequency, so control services are required to bring the frequency back to its nominal value and ensure it does not vary out of range.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] where Pm is the change in power of the system.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] If we have multiple generators, each might have its own R.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] This simple equation can be rearranged to find the change in power that corresponds to a given change in frequency.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Consumer loads expect voltage within a certain range, and the regulators require it be within a certain percent of the nominal voltage (for example, in the US it is ±5%).
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Reactive power can be used to compensate the voltage drops, but must be provided closer to the loads than real power needs (this is because reactive power tend to travel badly through the grid).
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Notice that voltage can be controlled also using transformer taps and voltage regulators.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Scheduling and dispatch are necessary because in most electrical systems energy storage is nearly zero, so at any instant, the power into the system (produced by a generator) must equal the power out of the system (demand from consumers).
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Since production must so closely match demand, careful scheduling and dispatch are necessary.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Usually performed by the independent system operator or transmission system operator, both are services dedicated to the commitment and coordination of the generation and transmission units in order to maintain the reliability of the power grid.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Scheduling refers to before-the-fact actions (like scheduling a generator to produce a certain amount of power the next week), while dispatch refers to the real-time control of the available resources.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Since production and demand must match so perfectly (see Scheduling and dispatch), operating reserves help make up the difference when production is too low.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] An operating reserve is a generator that can quickly be dispatched to ensure that there is sufficient energy generation to meet load.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Spinning reserves are generators that are already online and can rapidly increase their power output to meet fast changes in demand.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Spinning reserves are required because demand can vary on short timescales and rapid response is needed.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Other operating reserves are generators that can be dispatched by the operator to meet demand, but that cannot respond as quickly as spinning reserves, and grid battery storage that can respond within tens of milliseconds, generally faster than even spinning reserve.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] The grid integration of renewable generation simultaneously requires additional ancillary services and has the potential to provide ancillary services to the grid.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] The inverters that are installed with distributed generation systems and roof top solar systems have the potential to provide many of the ancillary services that are traditionally provided by spinning generators and voltage regulators.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] These services include reactive power compensation, voltage regulation, flicker control, active power filtering and harmonic cancellation.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Wind turbines with variable-speed generators have the potential to add synthetic inertia to the grid and assist in frequency control.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] CAISO tested the 131 MW Tule wind farm's synchronverter in 2018, and found it could perform some of the grid services similar or better than traditional generators.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Hydro-Québec began requiring synthetic inertia in 2005 as the first grid operator, demanding a temporary 6% power boost when countering frequency drop by combining the power electronics with the rotational inertia of a wind turbine rotor.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Similar requirements came into effect in Europe in 2016.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles have the potential to be utilized to provide ancillary services to the grid, specifically load regulation and spinning reserves.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles can behave like distributed energy storage and have the potential to discharge power back to the grid through bidirectional flow, referred to as vehicle-to-grid (V2G).
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] Plug-in electric vehicles have the ability to supply power at a fast rate which enables them to be used like spinning reserves and provide grid stability with the increased use of intermittent generation such as wind and solar.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] According to the study cited in the reference, which compared the profitability of offering operating reserve ancillary service with the sales of V2G energy from a fleet of vehicles, providing operating reserve regulation service is more profitable than selling V2G energy alone.
[src:circuit-breaker/ancillary-services] However, the technologies to utilize electric vehicles to provide ancillary services are not yet widely implemented, but there is much anticipation of their potential.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:circuit-breaker/ansi] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An **arc-fault circuit interrupter** (**AFCI**) or **arc-fault detection device** (**AFDD**) is a circuit breaker that breaks the circuit when it detects the electric arcs that are a signature of loose connections in home wiring.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Loose connections, which can develop over time, can sometimes become hot enough to ignite house fires.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An AFCI selectively distinguishes between a harmless arc (incidental to normal operation of switches, plugs, and brushed motors), and a potentially dangerous arc (that can occur, for example, in a lamp cord which has a broken conductor).
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In regions using 230 V, the combination of higher voltage and lower load currents lead to different conditions being required to initiate an arc fault that does not either burn clear or weld to a short circuit after a short time, and there are different arc characteristics once struck.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Because of this, in Western Europe (where in many countries a domestic supply may be 400V 3 phase) and the UK (where domestically a single phase 230V supply is common), adoption is slower, and their use is optional, only being mandated in specified high risk locations.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The Australian and New Zealand regulations – Wiring Rules (AS NZS 3000:2018) do not require installation of AFDDs in Australia.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] However, in New Zealand all final sub-circuits with ratings up to 20 A will require protection by an AFDD if they supply locations with significant fire risk, locations containing irreplaceable items, certain historic buildings, and socket-outlets in school sleeping accommodation.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Most sockets in these countries are on circuits rated at 20 A or less.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In the US, arc faults are said to be one of the leading causes for residential electrical fires.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Each year in the United States, over 40,000 fires are attributed to home electrical wiring.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] These fires result in over 350 deaths and over 1,400 injuries each year.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Conventional circuit breakers respond only to overloads and short circuits, so they do not protect against arcing conditions that produce erratic, and often reduced current.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs are devices designed to protect against fires caused by arcing faults in the home electrical wiring.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI circuitry continuously monitors the current and discriminates between normal and unwanted arcing conditions.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Once detected, the AFCI opens its internal contacts, thus de-energizing the circuit and reducing the potential for a fire to occur.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The electronics inside an AFCI breaker detect electrical current alternating at characteristic frequencies, usually around 100 kHz, known to be associated with wire arcing, which are sustained for more than a few milliseconds.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A *combination AFCI breaker* provides protection against parallel arcing (line to neutral), series arcing (a loose, broken, or otherwise high resistance segment in a single line), ground arcing (from line or neutral to ground), overload, and short circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI will open the circuit if dangerous arcing is detected.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] When installed as the first outlet on a branch circuit, AFCI receptacles provide series arc protection for the entire branch circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] They also provide parallel arc protection for the branch circuit starting at the AFCI receptacle.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Unlike AFCI breakers, AFCI receptacles may be used on any wiring system regardless of the panel.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Starting with the 1999 version of the *National Electrical Code* in the United States, and the 2002 version of the *Canadian Electrical Code* in Canada, the national codes require AFCIs in all circuits that feed outlets in bedrooms of dwelling units.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] They are also required in dormitory units.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Not all U.S. jurisdictions have adopted the NEC's AFCI requirements so it is important to check local code requirements.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The AFCI is intended to prevent fire from arcs.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI circuit breakers are designed to meet one of two standards as specified by UL 1699: "branch" type or "combination" type (note: the Canadian Electrical Code uses different terminology but similar technical requirements).
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A branch type AFCI trips on 75 amperes of arcing current from the line wire to either the neutral or ground wire.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A combination type adds series arcing detection to branch type performance.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Combination type AFCIs trip on 5 amperes of series arcing.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI receptacles are an alternative solution to AFCI breakers.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] These receptacles are designed to address the dangers associated with both types of potentially hazardous arcing: parallel and series.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI receptacles offer the benefit of localized *test* and *reset* with such buttons located on the face of the device.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This can save a journey to the breaker panel but can also encourage simply resetting by a user without investigating the underlying fault, as would presumably happen if someone with access to the electrical panel was notified.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In 2002, the NEC removed the word "receptacle", leaving "outlets", with the effect that lights and other wired-in devices such as ceiling fans within bedrooms were added to the requirement.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2005 code made it clearer that all outlets must be protected despite discussion in the code-making panel about excluding bedroom smoke detectors from the requirement.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] "Outlets" as defined in the NEC includes receptacles, light fixtures and smoke alarms, among other things.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Basically, any point where AC electricity is used to power something is an outlet.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] As of January 2008, only "combination type" AFCIs meet the NEC requirement.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2008 NEC requires the installation of combination-type AFCIs in all 15 and 20 ampere residential circuits with the exception of laundries, kitchens, bathrooms, garages, and unfinished basements, though many of these require GFCI protection.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The 2014 NEC adds kitchens and laundry rooms to the list of rooms requiring AFCI circuitry, as well as any devices (such as lighting) requiring protection.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] As of January 2023, there are a total of 6 means of protection covered as part of 210.12(A).
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A listed branch/feeder-type AFCI that is installed at the origin of the branch circuit working in combination with the listed outlet branch-circuit-type AFCI (OBC AFCI) installed at the first outlet box which must also be marked that it is the first outlet box of the branch circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This option includes a listed "Supplemental Arc Protection Circuit Breaker" which does not exist.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] There is no standard for this device and so this is not an option that can be used.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This option does have a single manufacturer who has a solution on the market.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (b) Maximum length for a 14 AWG conductor is 50 ft and the maximum length for a 12 AWG conductor is 70ft.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (c) The first outlet box has to be marked as such.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] (d) The circuit breaker and the OBC AFCI must be listed to meet the requirements of a system combination-type AFCI.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Options 5 and 6 are the same options as we've seen in this section in the past but just included as positive text instead of being an exception.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] In the UK, the Wiring Regulations 18th edition (BS 7671:2018) is the first edition to make any mention of arc fault devices, and indicate they may be installed if the design has an unusually high risk of fire from arc faults.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The annexes relating to testing indicate that when AFDDs are installed, their correct operation must be verified before completion, but the method of testing is not described.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This is in contrast to RCDs where a number of trip times at different fault current levels must be verified.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Most power circuits in these countries fall under this clause as the common sockets are 10 A and 15 A rating.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The Australian standards are used in Argentina, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands and Papua New Guinea.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs are designed to protect against fires caused by electrical arc faults.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] While the sensitivity of the AFCIs helps in the detection of arc faults, these breakers can also indicate false positives by identifying normal circuit behaviors as arc faults.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] For instance, lightning strikes provide voltage and current profiles that resemble arc faults, and vacuum cleaners and some laser printers trip AFCIs.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This nuisance tripping reduces the overall effectiveness of AFCIs.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Research into advancements in this area is being pursued.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Sensitivities and mitigation have been known since 2013.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCI circuit breakers include a standard inverse-time circuit breaker but provide no specific protection against "glowing" connections (also known as a high resistance connection), high line voltages, or low line voltages.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] An AFCI does not detect high line voltage caused by an open neutral in a multiwire branch circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] A multiwire branch circuit uses both energized wires of a 120–240 V split phase service.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] If the neutral is broken along the return path to the circuit breaker panel, devices connected from a 120 V leg to the neutral may experience excess voltage, up to twice normal.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Low line voltage can cause electromechanical relays to repeatedly turn off and on, or "chatter".
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] If current is flowing through the load contacts, it causes arcing across the contacts as they open.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] The arcing can oxidize, pit, and melt the contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] This process can increase the contact resistance, superheat the relay, and lead to fires.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] Power fault circuit interrupters are designed to prevent fires from low voltage across loads.
[src:circuit-breaker/arc-fault-circuit-interrupter] AFCIs may interfere with the operation of some power line communication technologies.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A **circuit breaker** is an electrical safety device designed to protect an electrical circuit from damage caused by current in excess of that which the equipment can safely carry (overcurrent).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Its basic function is to interrupt current flow to protect equipment and to prevent fire.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Unlike a fuse, which interrupts once and then must be replaced, a circuit breaker can be reset (either manually or automatically) to resume normal operation.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are commonly installed in distribution boards.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Apart from its safety purpose, a circuit breaker is also often used as a main switch to manually disconnect ("rack out") and connect ("rack in") electrical power to a whole electrical sub-network.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are made in varying current ratings, from devices that protect low-current circuits or individual household appliances, to switchgear designed to protect high-voltage circuits feeding an entire city.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Any device which protects against excessive current by automatically removing power from a faulty system, such as a circuit breaker or fuse, can be referred to as an *over-current protection device* (*OCPD*).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] An early form of circuit breaker was described by Thomas Edison in an 1879 patent application, although his commercial power distribution system used fuses.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Its purpose was to protect lighting circuit wiring from accidental short circuits and overloads.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A modern miniature circuit breaker similar to the ones now in use was patented by Brown, Boveri & Cie in 1924.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Hugo Stotz, an engineer who had sold his company to Brown, Boveri & Cie, was credited as the inventor on German patent 458392.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Stotz's invention was the forerunner of the modern thermal-magnetic breaker commonly used in household load centers to this day.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Interconnection of multiple generator sources into an electrical grid required the development of circuit breakers with increasing voltage ratings and increased ability to safely interrupt the increasing short-circuit currents produced by networks.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Simple air-break manual switches produced hazardous arcs when interrupting high-voltage circuits; these gave way to oil-enclosed contacts, and various forms using the directed flow of pressurized air, or pressurized oil, to cool and interrupt the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] By 1935, the specially constructed circuit breakers used at the Boulder Dam project used eight series breaks and pressurized oil flow to interrupt faults of up to 2,500 MVA, in three AC cycles.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] All circuit breaker systems have common features in their operation, but details vary substantially depending on the voltage class, current rating and type of the circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The circuit breaker must first detect a fault condition.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In small mains and low-voltage circuit breakers, this is usually done within the device itself.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Typically, the heating or magnetic effects of electric current are employed.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers for large currents or high voltages are usually arranged with protective relay pilot devices to sense a fault condition and to operate the opening mechanism.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These typically require a separate power source, such as a battery, although some high-voltage circuit breakers are self-contained with current transformers, protective relays, and internal power sources.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Once a fault is detected, the circuit breaker contacts must open to interrupt the circuit; this is commonly done using mechanically stored energy contained within the breaker, such as a spring or compressed air to separate the contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A breaker may also use the higher current caused by the fault to separate the contacts, via thermal expansion or increased magnetic field.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A small circuit breaker typically has a manual control lever to switch the circuit off or reset a tripped breaker, while a larger unit may use a solenoid to trip the mechanism, and an electric motor to restore energy to springs (which rapidly separate contacts when the breaker is tripped).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The circuit breaker contacts must carry the load current without excessive heating, and must also withstand the heat of the arc produced when interrupting (opening) the circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Contacts are made of copper or copper alloys, silver alloys and other highly conductive materials.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Service life of the contacts is limited by the erosion of contact material due to arcing while interrupting the current.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Miniature and molded-case circuit breakers are usually discarded when the contacts have worn, but power circuit breakers and high-voltage circuit breakers have replaceable contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] When a high current or voltage is interrupted, an arc is generated.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The maximum length of the arc is generally proportional to the voltage while the intensity (or heat) is proportional to the current.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This arc must be contained, cooled and extinguished in a controlled way, so that the gap between the contacts can again withstand the voltage in the circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Different circuit breakers use vacuum, air, insulating gas, or oil as the medium the arc forms in.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Finally, once the fault condition has been cleared, the contacts must again be closed to restore power to the interrupted circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Low-voltage **miniature circuit breakers** (**MCB**) use air alone to extinguish the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These circuit breakers contain so-called arc chutes, a stack of mutually insulated parallel metal plates that divide and cool the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Splitting the arc into smaller arcs makes the arc cooler as the arc voltage increases and serves as an additional impedance that limits the current through the circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The current-carrying parts near the contacts provide easy deflection of the arc into the arc chutes by a magnetic force of a current path, although magnetic blowout coils or permanent magnets could also deflect the arc into the arc chute (used on circuit breakers for higher ratings).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The number of plates in the arc chute is dependent on the short-circuit rating and nominal voltage of the circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In larger ratings, oil circuit breakers rely upon vaporization of some of the oil to blast a jet of oil through the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Gas (usually sulfur hexafluoride) circuit breakers sometimes stretch the arc using a magnetic field, and then rely upon the dielectric strength of the sulfur hexafluoride (SF6) to quench the stretched arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Vacuum circuit breakers have minimal arcing (as there is nothing to ionize other than the contact material).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The arc is quenched when it is stretched a very small amount (less than 3 mm (0.1 in)).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Vacuum circuit breakers are frequently used in modern medium-voltage switch gear to 38,000 volts.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Air circuit breakers may use compressed air to blow out the arc, or alternatively, the contacts are rapidly swung into a small sealed chamber, the escaping of the displaced air thus blowing out the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are usually able to terminate all current very quickly: typically the arc is extinguished between 30 and 150 ms after the mechanism has been tripped, depending upon age and construction of the device.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The maximum current value and let-through energy determine the quality of the circuit breakers.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are rated both by the normal current that they are expected to carry, and the maximum short-circuit current that they can safely interrupt.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This latter figure is the **ampere interrupting capacity** (**AIC**) of the breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Under short-circuit conditions, the calculated or measured maximum prospective short-circuit current may be many times the normal, rated current of the circuit.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] When electrical contacts open to interrupt a large current, there is a tendency for an arc to form between the opened contacts, which would allow the current to continue.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This condition can create conductive ionized gases and molten or vaporized metal, which can cause the further continuation of the arc or create additional short circuits, potentially resulting in the explosion of the circuit breaker and the equipment that it is installed in.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Therefore, circuit breakers incorporate various features to divide and extinguish the arcs.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The maximum short-circuit current that a breaker can interrupt is determined by testing.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Application of a breaker in a circuit with a prospective short-circuit current higher than the breaker's interrupting capacity rating may result in failure of the breaker to safely interrupt a fault.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In a worst-case scenario, a breaker may successfully interrupt a fault only to explode when reset.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Typical domestic panel circuit breakers are rated to interrupt 10 kA (10,000 A) short-circuit current.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Miniature circuit breakers used to protect control circuits or small appliances may not have sufficient interrupting capacity to use at a panel board; these circuit breakers are called "supplemental circuit protectors" to distinguish them from distribution-type circuit breakers.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are manufactured with standard ratings, using a system of preferred numbers to create a useful selection of ratings.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A miniature circuit breaker has a fixed trip setting; changing the operating current value requires replacing the whole circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers with higher ratings can have adjustable trip settings, allowing fewer standardized products to be used, adjusted to the applicable precise ratings when installed.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] For example, a circuit breaker with a 400 ampere *frame size* might have its over-current detection threshold set only 300 amperes where that rating is appropriate.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] For low-voltage distribution circuit breakers an international standard, IEC 60898-1, defines *rated current* as the maximum current that a breaker is designed to carry continuously.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers are also rated by the maximum fault current that they can interrupt; this allows use of more economical devices on systems unlikely to develop the high short-circuit current found on, for example, a large commercial building distribution system.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In the United States, Underwriters Laboratories (UL) certifies equipment ratings, called Series Ratings (or "integrated equipment ratings") for circuit breaker equipment used for buildings.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Power circuit breakers and medium- and high-voltage circuit breakers used for industrial or electric power systems are designed and tested to ANSI or IEEE standards in the C37 series.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] For example, standard C37.16 lists preferred frame size current ratings for power circuit breakers in the range of 600 to 5000 amperes.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Trip current settings and time–current characteristics of these breakers are generally adjustable.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] For medium- and high-voltage circuit breakers used in switchgear, substations and generating stations, relatively few standard frame sizes are generally manufactured.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These circuit breakers are usually controlled by separate protective relay systems, offering adjustable tripping current and time settings as well as allowing for more complex protection schemes.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Many classifications of circuit breakers can be made, based on their features such as voltage class, construction type, interrupting type, and structural features.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The characteristics of low-voltage circuit breakers are given by international standards such as IEC 947.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These circuit breakers are often installed in draw-out enclosures that allow removal and interchange without dismantling the switchgear.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Large low-voltage molded-case and power circuit breakers may have electric motor operators so they can open and close under remote control.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These may form part of an automatic transfer switch system for standby power.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Low-voltage circuit breakers are also made for direct-current (DC) applications, such as for subway lines.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Direct current requires special breakers because the arc is continuous—unlike an AC arc, which tends to go out on each half cycle, a direct-current circuit breaker has a blow-out coil that generates a magnetic field that rapidly stretches the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Small circuit breakers are either installed directly in equipment or arranged in breaker panels.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The DIN-rail-mounted thermal-magnetic miniature circuit breaker is the most common style in modern domestic consumer units and commercial electrical distribution boards throughout Europe.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Actuator mechanism – forces the contacts together or apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Contacts – allow current when touching and break the current when moved apart.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Calibration screw – allows the manufacturer to precisely adjust the trip current of the device after assembly.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A *magnetic* circuit breaker uses a solenoid (electromagnet) whose pulling force increases with the current.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Certain designs utilize electromagnetic forces in addition to those of the solenoid.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The circuit breaker contacts are held closed by a latch.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] As the current in the solenoid increases beyond the rating of the circuit breaker, the solenoid's pull releases the latch, which lets the contacts open by spring action.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] They are the most commonly used circuit breakers in the United States.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The thermal portion of the circuit breaker provides a time-response feature that trips the circuit breaker sooner for larger over-currents but allows smaller overloads to persist for a longer time.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This allows short current spikes such as are produced when a motor or other non-resistive load is switched on.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] With a very large over-current, such as may be caused short circuit, the magnetic element trips the circuit breaker with no intentional additional delay.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A *magnetic–hydraulic* circuit breaker uses a solenoid coil to provide operating force to open the contacts.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A magnetic–hydraulic breaker incorporates a hydraulic time delay feature using a viscous fluid.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A spring restrains the core until the current exceeds the breaker rating.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] During an overload, the speed of the solenoid motion is restricted by the fluid.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The delay permits brief current surges beyond normal running current for motor starting, energizing equipment, etc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Short-circuit currents provide sufficient solenoid force to release the latch regardless of core position thus bypassing the delay feature.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Ambient temperature affects the time delay but does not affect the current rating of a magnetic breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A large power circuit breaker, such as one applied in circuits of more than 1000 volts, may incorporate hydraulic elements in the contact operating mechanism.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Hydraulic energy may be supplied by a pump or stored in accumulators.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These form a distinct type from oil-filled circuit breakers where oil is the arc-extinguishing medium.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] To provide simultaneous breaking on multiple circuits from a fault on any one, circuit breakers may be made as a ganged assembly.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This is a very common requirement for three-phase systems, where breaking may be either three- or four-pole (solid or switched neutral).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Some makers make ganging kits to allow groups of single-phase breakers to be interlinked as required.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In the US, where split-phase supplies are common, in a branch circuit with more than one live conductor, each live conductor must be protected by a breaker pole.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] To ensure that all live conductors are interrupted when any pole trips, a *common-trip* set of breakers must be used.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These may either contain two or three tripping mechanisms within one case or, for small breakers, have the breakers externally tied together via their operating handles.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Two-pole common-trip breakers are common on 120/240-volt systems where 240 volt loads (including major appliances or further distribution boards) span the two live wires.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Three-pole common-trip breakers are typically used to supply three-phase power to powerful motors or further distribution boards.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This is why only common-trip breakers must be used when neutral wire switching is needed.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These are often used to cut the power when a high-risk event occurs, such as a fire or flood alarm, or another electrical condition, such as over-voltage detection.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Shunt trips may be a user-fitted accessory to a standard breaker or supplied as an integral part of a circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers rated between 1 and 72 kV may be assembled into metal-enclosed switchgear line-ups for indoor use or may be individual components installed outdoors in a substation.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Air-break circuit breakers replaced oil-filled units for indoor applications, but are now themselves being replaced by vacuum circuit breakers (up to about 40.5 kV).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Like the high-voltage circuit breakers described below, these are also operated by current-sensing protective relays operated through current transformers.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The characteristics of MV breakers are given by international standards such as IEC 62271.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers nearly always use separate current sensors and protective relays instead of relying on built-in thermal or magnetic overcurrent sensors.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers may be connected into the circuit by bolted connections to bus bars or wires, especially in outdoor switchyards.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Medium-voltage circuit breakers in switchgear line-ups are often built with draw-out construction, allowing breaker removal without disturbing power circuit connections, using a motor-operated or hand-cranked mechanism to separate the breaker from its enclosure.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Electrical power transmission networks are protected and controlled by high-voltage breakers.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The definition of *high voltage* varies but in power transmission work is usually thought to be 72.5 kV or higher, according to a recent definition by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] High-voltage breakers are nearly always solenoid-operated, with current sensing protective relays operated through current transformers.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In substations the protective relay scheme can be complex, protecting equipment and buses from various types of overload or ground/earth fault.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Due to environmental and cost concerns over insulating oil spills, most new breakers use SF6 gas to quench the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Circuit breakers can be classified as *live tank*, where the enclosure that contains the breaking mechanism is at line potential, or *dead tank* with the enclosure at earth potential.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] High-voltage AC circuit breakers are routinely available with ratings up to 765 kV.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] 1,200 kV breakers were launched by Siemens in November 2011, followed by ABB in April the following year.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] High-voltage circuit breakers used on transmission systems may be arranged to allow a single pole of a three-phase line to trip, instead of tripping all three poles; for some classes of faults this improves the system stability and availability.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] High-voltage direct current circuit breakers are still a field of research as of 2015.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Such breakers would be useful to interconnect HVDC transmission systems.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A sulfur hexafluoride circuit breaker uses contacts surrounded by sulfur hexafluoride gas to quench the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] They are most often used for transmission-level voltages and may be incorporated into compact gas-insulated switchgear.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In cold climates, supplemental heating or different gas mixtures are used for high voltage circuit breakers, due to liquefaction of the SF6 gas.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In some northern power grids, gas mixtures of N2 and SF6, or CF4 and SF6 are installed in puffer-type HVCB to quench the arc without any liquefaction of the gas.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The minimum temperature ratings of these models are as low as -50 °C for some northern substations.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The disconnecting circuit breaker (DCB) was introduced in 2000 and is a high-voltage circuit breaker modeled after the SF6-breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] It presents a technical solution where the disconnecting function is integrated in the breaking chamber, eliminating the need for separate disconnectors.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This increases the availability, since open-air disconnecting switch main contacts need maintenance every 2–6 years, while modern circuit breakers have maintenance intervals of 15 years.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Implementing a DCB solution also reduces the space requirements within the substation, and increases the reliability, due to the lack of separate disconnectors.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In order to further reduce the required space of substation, as well as simplifying the design and engineering of the substation, a fiber optic current sensor (FOCS) can be integrated with the DCB.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A 420 kV DCB with integrated FOCS can reduce a substation's footprint with over 50% compared to a conventional solution of live tank breakers with disconnectors and current transformers, due to reduced material and no additional insulation medium.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In 2012, ABB presented a 75 kV high-voltage breaker that uses carbon dioxide as the medium to extinguish the arc.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The carbon dioxide breaker works on the same principles as an SF6 breaker and can also be produced as a disconnecting circuit breaker.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] By switching from SF6 to CO2, it is possible to reduce the CO2 emissions by 10 tons during the product's life cycle.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] A smart circuit breaker is an electronic overcurrent protection device that integrates high-frequency sensors and Internet-of-Things (IoT) connectivity to provide intelligent control and real-time monitoring of electrical circuits.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Unlike traditional circuit breakers, smart breakers utilize digital logic and communication to augment their operation.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Protocols such as Wi-Fi, Zigbee, or cellular networks are used to gather and transmit granular electrical data including voltage, current, and power quality .
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] These devices are implemented either as modular components that replace standard breakers in a compatible load center or as core elements of a comprehensive smart electrical panel.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] This technology transforms the breaker box into an active "energy hub," often capable of decision-making and precise circuit-level metering.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] One of the primary use case for smart circuit breakers in residential environments is the optimization of home energy management systems (HEMS), especially those incorporating solar arrays, electric vehicle (EV) chargers, and battery storage .
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Through mobile applications, users can remotely actuate circuits, schedule high-intensity loads to run during off-peak hours for cost savings, and implement dynamic load shedding to prioritize essential appliances during power outages.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] Using these can provide significant benefits in reducing battery cycling and increasing the power capacity of existing electrical service .
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] In commercial and industrial settings, smart breakers are integrated with Building Management Systems (BMS) to enable advanced functions such as automated tenant billing, demand response participation, and predictive maintenance through anomaly detection.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] By intelligently managing demand, these systems allow facilities to scale energy-intensive infrastructure without necessitating costly utility service upgrades.
[src:circuit-breaker/circuit-breaker] The following types are described in separate articles.
